TPG Telecom Ltd | Asia Pacific
Key debate: how fast can the new TPG grow EBITDA... and what is the right multiple to pay for this? We keep UW
WHAT'S CHANGEDTPG Telecom Ltd (TPG.AX)FromToPrice TargetA$4.35A$4.70
Reaction to earningsUnchanged— In-line— Largely unchangedImpact to our thesisFinancial results versus consensusDirection of next 12-month consensus EPS
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research

H1 results showed \(+2\%\) Mobile services rev growth, solid, but only in- line. Cash flow improved. Key debate is on the new TPG (ex- fibre) sustainable earnings growth prospects). In telco space, we prefer TLS for absolute dividend growth and ABB for capital appreciation potential. Keep UW.

CY25 H1 results solid - Service revs \(+2.2\%\) yoy - driven by 100k mobile subscribers from Optus regional network sharing. Op. FCF \(+24\%\) to A\$246m. One key debate is will the new TPG (ex- fibre) be de- rated? On our proforma estimates the new TPG trades on \(\sim 7.5x\) FY26 EV/EBITDA.

TPG delivered solid earnings and FCF growth, underpinned by disciplined cost management and improved mobile subscriber momentum. Operational metrics were mixed across segments, but the standout was the addition of 100,000 net mobile subscribers, driven by regional network expansion and the Optus MOCN partnership. TBG also completed divestment of its fibre network and enterprise business for an EV of A\$5.25bn and A\$4.7bn in net cash proceeds.

We lift our PT to A\$4.70/share: On the positive side, cash in alleviates debt concerns and key positives include: i) TPG should be a capex lighter business, ii) EPS boost from lower D&A + interest expense, and iii) TPG should be able to sustain a rising dividend. TPG is a well- run telco, with a more positive outlook now. But within our coverage universe, we continue to prefer market leader TLS (OW) as the sector's quality defensive, where we have higher confidence of a rising DPS trajectory; while for capital growth potential we prefer ABB (OW). We estimate TPG trades at \(\sim 7.5x\) FY26E EBITDA, adjusted for growth it is relatively expensive.
MORGAN STANLEY AUSTRALIA LIMITED+

After review of TPG's assessed as in- line 1H CY25 results (August 28, 2025) and reiteration of all of its guidance for the full year, there is no change to our view. We keep our UW rating, with a price target of \(A\) 4.70/share, implied downside of \(\sim 12\%\) . We recognise as positive news, that TPG has finalised the sale of its fibre + fixed EGW assets to Vocus and we update our model to reflect the changes.
Three key points to our thesis:

1. Has TPG's earnings risk profile increased (ex-fibre)? The near-term outlook for mobile sub growth (due to MOCN) and mobile pricing is positive, in our view, as it should underpin modest positive near-term mobile EBITDA growth. But, medium-term hopes for growth could be more challenging, in our view, with a 3-year EBITDA CAGR of \(3\%\) . We see the new TPG (ex-fibre) left mostly as a consumer Mobile business, the #3 in the AU market and a reseller of NBN consumer broadband ... as such we are mindful of TPG being more vulnerable to any disturbance in the current favourable mobile landscape.

2. Capital allocation priorities? We have not agreed with every major strategic decision in the past, e.g. rather than sell its fibre network we would have preferred TPG cut its dividend to zero for several years, to accelerate debt reduction (for detail, see our in-depth report: Should TPG cut its dividend to zero? ... yes we think so (15 Nov 2023)). But, management have executed well, and that was in the past. Looking forward, we will be watching the actions to maximise returns for all shareholders, including minority shareholders.

3. Valuation? ... key to our UW rating ... is that we see more attractive risk/return elsewhere in our A&NZ telco coverage - we prefer TLS for dividend growth ... and we prefer ABB for capital appreciation potential. At the current \(\sim A\) 5.3/share, we estimate TPG is trading at \(\sim 7.6x\) EBITDA after factoring in the fibre sale to Vocus, \(A\) 1.7bn debt payment and \(\sim A\) 3bn capital return. In our AU telco coverage universe, we prefer Telstra (TLS, OW) for its rising absolute dividend potential at 8.5x; and we prefer Aussie Broadband (ABB, OW) for its greater capital growth potential at 10x EBITDA but 17% 3-year CAGR (see Exhibit 1, page 1 and Exhibit 8, page 6, for our estimates.)

We derive a fundamental value range of \(\mathsf{A}\Phi 3.7 - \mathsf{A}\Phi 5.85 / \mathsf{TPG}\) share, from three methodologies: discounted cashflow (DCF), SoTP (EBITDA- based) and target P/E. Our price target represents the approximate midpoint of this range at \(\mathsf{A}\Phi 4.7 / \mathsf{share}\) . The catalyst for tweaking our multiple assumptions is we see a wider range of risk/reward outcomes for TPG vs. its main Australian telco peer Telstra. Factors contributing to TPG's higher volatility include: its weaker market position – TLS is #1 in mobile, broadband, and enterprise vs. TPG #3, #2, and #3; TPG's relatively higher debt levels/leverage; and less optionality for TPG given the divestment of its towers business and fibre assets.
Our bull case value is unchanged at \(\mathsf{A}\Phi 8 / \mathsf{sh}\) and our bear case value remains \(\mathsf{A}\Phi 2 / \mathsf{sh}\) . See Risk Reward - TPG Telecom Ltd (TPG.AX) for detail.

- P/E value rises to \(\mathsf{A}\Phi 3.69 / \mathsf{share}\) from \(\mathsf{A}\Phi 2.86 / \mathsf{share}\) : Based on our cash EPS of 20c (vs. reported EPS of 1.3cps) for CY25E and a 18x multiple (was 42x – lowered given lower EPS CAGR). Our P/E value rises as TPG will be retiring \(\mathsf{A}\Phi 1.7\mathsf{bn}\) of debt that improves the NPAT.  
- DCF value falls to \(\mathsf{A}\Phi 5.85 / \mathsf{share}\) from \(\mathsf{A}\Phi 6.4 / \mathsf{share}\) : WACC 10.0%, terminal growth rate 2.0% - from lower terminal estimates.  
- SOTP value falls to \(\mathsf{A}\Phi 5.43 / \mathsf{share}\) from \(\mathsf{A}\Phi 5.44 / \mathsf{share}\) : No changes to our blended 6.7x multiple. Lower earnings are offset by the net cash proceeds of \(\Phi 4.7\mathsf{bn}\) from EG&W sale to Vocus.

Cautious view due to: i) earnings risks and ii) capital allocation risk
We consider the risk-reward balance as unattractive vs. other Australian telco alternatives and rate TPG Underweight. Three key points:

Earnings risk: Mobile revenue and EBITDA growth prospects are higher as the #3 player in a three- player market. TPG is not a price leader. We also see risk to EPS from high debt exposure and only 2x EBIT to net interest cover.

Capital allocation risk: We have some concerns that the 100% sale of Infra assets and previously mobile towers assets may diminish TPG's long- term earnings power. Unattractive valuation: TPG's earnings carry higher risk, in our view, but the shares trade near parity on valuation multiples vs. AU integrated telco peer TLS.
Source: Refinitiv, Morgan Stanley Research
Contrarian: Negative View descriptions of Risk Rewards Themes here

Stronger Australian economy + rising consumer/corporate spending on telco products and services: EBITDA is 20% higher than in base case. TPG exceeds our base- case cost- out, getting \~A\(300mn from Vodafone Australia merger over five years. TPG makes meaningful gains in market share in fixed- line, mobiles and corporate/enterprise. In addition to sale of mobile towers, TPG may pursue monetisation of other telco infrastructure assets at attractive valuations.

Gradual improvement in Australian economy + steady consumer/corporate spending on telco products and services: TPG returns to mid- single- digit organic EBITDA growth starting from CY25- 26E. TPG achieves our base- case cost- out of \~A\(200mn from Vodafone Australia merger within five years from completion. TPG market share in fixed- line, mobiles and corporate/enterprise remains steady.
Recession in Australian economy + falling consumer/corporate spending on telco products and services and technological disruption. TPG suffers market share losses in all segments

Fundamental valuation range of \(A\) 4.91- 6.93/share based on three methodologies. We set the approximate midpoint of \(A\) 6.0/share as our price target.

DCF \(A\) 6.93/share. WACC \(10\%\) (in line with telco average) + TGR \(3.0\%\) . SoTP \(A\) 4.9/share. Target EBITDA multiple of 9.5x [10x?] applied to core ABB business (ex Symbio) and 7.5x applied to Symbio on a standalone basis FY26e. P/E \(A\) 5.87/share. FY26E EPS 20c at 30x (moderate premium to industry for growth).

We use three valuation methods — target P/E, SOTP and DCF — to derive a fundamental valuation range of \(A\) 4.56- 5.24/share. From this we select an approximate midpoint of \(A\) 4.95/share as our price target.

P/E value: \(A\) 4.56/share (FY26E core EPS of 17c at 17x; NBN recurring of 5c at 40x) SOTP value: \(A\) 5.24/share (range 5- 10x EBITDA for core and 15x for InfraCo + Mobile Towers). DCF value: \(A\) 4.69/share (8.9% WACC, 2% TGR).
Increased mobile market share + higher ARPU + higher mobile EBITDA margins Lift in broadband margins from cost- out and 5GFW Higher value for TLS InfraCo assets Rise in DPS profile above consensus

- Technological advancements continue to drive margin leakage in Data and Connectivity- Industry structure change (e.g., NBN)- Competition (TPG/Vodafone and VOC in enterprise, TPG/Vodafone and Optus in mobile)
